description.narrative:
The intended outcome of Education for Sustainable Peace in Rwanda (ESPR) is to contribute to sustainable peace in Rwanda through peace education within formal and non-formal education and influence related policies through research.ESPR will achieve this by working with three key change agents ('Boundary Partners'): 1) Educators, 2) Youth and 3) Decision-makers &amp; Researchers. The programme will build a sustained legacy that will promote critical thinking, empathy and personal responsibility among Educators and Youth to improve social cohesion, and will catalyse pluralistic and constructive exchange on genocide and peacebuilding topics to improve policy and practice that will promote social cohesion and sustainable peace in Rwanda. 
Update (extension)
Aegis submitted a proposal to amend the agreement for Education for Sustainable Peace in Rwanda (ESPR) programme for three months (July-September 2021 in order to bridge the period between the end of the programme in June until the new programme is designed and appraised by the Embassy.
Rationale of the extension
Under ESPR, Aegis aims to build resilience against identity-based violence through Peace and Values Education (PVE) targeting formal and non-formal education.
As Aegis transitions from ESPR to its next three-year programme, in coordination with Interpeace and Never Again Rwanda, there is a need to develop a coherent approach and implementation framework that will allow better coordination and synergy, Value for Money and additional outcomes.
The addendum period will serve as a bridge between the current programme and the upcoming programme, which is due to start on October 1st, 2021. The extension will allow Aegis to maintain the key human resources and capacities that it has built internally during ESPR, to finalize the proposal for the upcoming programme, cooperate with the Embassy during the appraisal, and to make a number of necessary studies and analyses, some of which would otherwise be done during an inception phase of the new programme.
The addendum will also allow Aegis, Interpeace and Never Again Rwanda to set the ground for their joint implementation framework, which is meant to reduce transaction costs as a result of better coordination. A concept note on the joint programming, developed by the three organisations, is shared with the Embassy in advance of signinig this extension with Aegis. 
Outputs
1. An agreed upon implementation framework between the three organizations established;
2. Intervention convergence and divergence between the three organizations identified;
3. The opportunity that comes with the choice to work jointly and/or separately (where there is convergence) assessed;
4. A conflict analysis conducted;
5. Training targeting staff (new content and crosscutting issues) conducted; Review and confirmation of content done;
6. Training sessions for the three organizations (Aegis, Never Again and Interpeace) and Radio La Benevolencija as Aegis downstream partner conducted;
7. A stakeholder review and consultations (including REB and other policy makers) conducted;
8. Feedback from key boundary partners collected (including field work);
9. Behavioural baseline information established; A participatory programme design workshop organized;
10. Proposal will be developed and submitted
